Dealing with projections¶

In [32]:
# It's WGS-84, a spherical coordinate system AKA 'epsg:4326'
# It can't be shown on a flat surface but when you try typically gets projected into a Platte Carree projection
# This the the CRS used by GPS/Satellites and GeoJSON
ax = world.plot()
ax.set_title("WGS84 (lat/lon)")
Out[32]:
Text(0.5,1,'WGS84 (lat/lon)')
In [33]:
# Set the projection to the Mercator projection (epsg=3395)
world = world.to_crs(epsg=3395)
ax = world.plot()
ax.set_title("Mercator")
Out[33]:
Text(0.5,1,'Mercator')
In [34]:
# Set the projection to Polar Stereographic (epsg=3995)
world = world.to_crs(epsg=3995)
ax = world.plot()
ax.set_title("Polar Stereographic")
Out[34]:
Text(0.5,1,'Polar Stereographic')

Looking at eclipses¶

Data: Eclipse data downloaded by event in KMZ format here: http://xjubier.free.fr/en/site_pages/SolarEclipsesGoogleEarth.html

Process: Used the Esri KML to Layer tool on each KMZ to export to a layer file. Exported the polygon portion of said layer file to a shapefile Used Esri's Merge(Data Management) tool to merge all the individual polygon shapefiles into one.

In [65]:
# We can see that there are a few cities that intersect my path! But we want to know which ones.
# Do a spatial join to get the intersection
from geopandas.tools import sjoin
ecities = gpd.sjoin(cities, myeclipse, how='inner', op='intersects')
ecities.head()

import folium

# Let's find the centroid of the eclipse we chose, so that we can center our folum map on it
x = ecities.centroid.x.values[0]
y = ecities.centroid.y.values[0]
print('y: ' + str(y) + ', x: ' + str(x))

y: -38.74002683640157, x: -72.96002750821697
In [282]:

map_carto

In [283]:
folium.GeoJson(myeclipse,name='Eclipse Path').add_to(map_carto)

fg=folium.FeatureGroup(name="Pika")

for name,row in ecities.iterrows():
    popup_text = 'Location {}'.format(row['NAME'])
    lat = row['LATITUDE']
    lon = row['LONGITUDE']
    fg.add_child(folium.Marker(location=[lat,lon],popup=(folium.Popup(popup_text))))
    
map_carto.add_child(fg)
map_carto
